Polish Stocks: Enea, KGHM, Lotos, Milkiland, Orlen, PBG Shares

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i
-- 
2011-04-08T12:53:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-08/polish-stocks-enea-milkiland-pbg-shares-are-active-in-warsaw.html
Poland’s WIG20 Index advanced 7.14,
or 0.2 percent, to 2,936.09 at 2:06 p.m. in Warsaw, extending
this week’s gain to 2.1 percent.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
 Warsaw Stock Exchange  today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Enea SA (ENA)   gained for a second day, adding 0.15
zloty, or 0.8 percent, to 19.6 zloty. Poland’s third-largest
power utility is only interested in buying companies operating
on the energy market, Chief Executive Officer Maciej Owczarek
told Parkiet newspaper.  Enea has no plans to buy shares of coal mine Lubelski
Wegiel Bogdanka SA, Enea said on April 5.  KGHM Polska Miedz SA (KGH)  , the copper producer with the
biggest European mine output, climbed 4 zloty, or 2.1 percent,
to 198.1 zloty, heading for the highest close since the stock
started trading in 1997. Copper rose to a one-month high in
London as reports signaling continued economic expansion fed
speculation global growth will sustain demand for industrial
metals.  Milkiland NV (MLK)   advanced for the first time in four
days, increasing 0.8 zloty, or 2 percent, to 41.4 zloty.
UniCredit SpA recommended buying shares of the dairy company
that operates in Russia and Ukraine, setting its share-price
estimate at 50 zloty.  PBG SA (PBG)   climbed for a second day, increasing 2.6
zloty, or 1.5 percent, to 178.6 zloty. Poland’s third-largest
builder and Spain’s Obrascon Huarte Lain SA signed a letter of
intent to work together on construction projects for the  energy
industry , including pipelines and storage facilities, in
countries such a Mexico, Brazil and Russia.  Separately, PBG said 2011 net income will be about 200
million zloty ($73 million) on revenue of 2.3 billion zloty.  PKN Orlen SA (PKN PW), Poland’s biggest oil company, gained
1.05 zloty, or 1.9 percent, to 57.55 zloty.  Grupa Lotos SA (LTS)  , the second-largest refiner, added 0.38 zloty, or 0.8
percent, to 48.33 zloty. Oil rose above $111 a barrel in New
York and surpassed $124 a barrel in London for the first time
since 2008 as a fire burned at Libya’s Sarir field, bolstering
concern that unrest in the region will further reduce supply.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Pawel Kozlowski in Warsaw 
